## 👑 KING RULE — Security Is Non-Negotiable

> **THE APPLICATION MUST BE RESILIENT TO HACKING ATTACKS AT ALL LAYERS. SECURITY IS A FIRST-CLASS CONCERN — NOT AN AFTERTHOUGHT.**

### 23. API Security

#### 23.1 Authentication & Authorization
- Every admin API route MUST call `requireAdmin()` from `lib/auth-guard.ts` — **no exceptions**.
- Never trust client-provided user IDs or roles: always derive identity from the server-side session (NextAuth JWT).
- Principle of least privilege: admin API routes must check role (`ADMIN` or `SUPER_ADMIN`) before executing destructive operations.
- Session tokens: use `httpOnly`, `secure`, `sameSite=lax` cookies (NextAuth default — do not override).

#### 23.2 Input Validation — ZERO TRUST ON ALL INPUTS
- **ALL API route bodies MUST be validated with Zod** before any processing or DB write.
- Never pass `req.body` directly to Prisma — always destructure validated fields.
- Validate query strings and path params with Zod on admin endpoints.
- Use `z.string().trim().max(N)` on all string fields — prevent oversized payloads.
- Pattern example (required in every mutation route):
  ```ts
  const schema = z.object({ name: z.string().trim().min(1).max(200) });
  const result = schema.safeParse(await req.json());
  if (!result.success) return NextResponse.json({ error: result.error.flatten() }, { status: 400 });
  const { name } = result.data;
  ```

#### 23.3 SQL Injection Prevention
- **ONLY use Prisma ORM** for all database access — Prisma parameterizes all queries automatically.
- If raw SQL is ever required, use **tagged template literals** (`prisma.$queryRaw\`...\``) — NEVER string concatenation.
- Never interpolate user input into raw SQL strings.

#### 23.4 Rate Limiting (Required on All Public Mutations)
- The following endpoints MUST have rate limiting via `@upstash/ratelimit`:

| Endpoint | Limit | Key |
|----------|-------|-----|
| `POST /api/checkout` | 5 req/min | IP |
| `POST /api/coupons/apply` | 10 req/min | IP |
| `POST /api/cart/validate` | 20 req/min | IP |
| `POST /api/orders` | 5 req/min | IP |
| `POST /api/ai/*` | 10 req/hour | Admin user ID |
| Admin login attempts | 5 req/15min | IP |

- Rate limit middleware pattern (in each protected route):
  ```ts
  const ip = req.headers.get('x-forwarded-for') ?? '127.0.0.1';
  const { success } = await ratelimit.limit(ip);
  if (!success) return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Too many requests' }, { status: 429 });
  ```

#### 23.5 CSRF Protection
- Next.js App Router API routes with `Content-Type: application/json` are inherently CSRF-safe (browsers cannot send JSON cross-origin without CORS).
- For form submissions using `multipart/form-data` or `application/x-www-form-urlencoded`, verify the `Origin` header equals `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL`.
- Never use GET routes for mutations (state changes, writes, deletes).

#### 23.6 Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Prevention
- React auto-escapes JSX by default — **never use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`** unless absolutely required and sanitized with `DOMPurify`.
- Never inject user-provided content into `<script>` tags or event handlers.
- Content-Security-Policy header MUST be set in `next.config.mjs` (see `next.config.mjs` security headers section).
- Do NOT trust `req.headers.referer` or `req.headers.origin` as authentication — these can be spoofed.

#### 23.7 Secret Management
- ALL secrets MUST live in `.env.dev` (dev) or `.env.prd` (production) — never in source code.
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix ONLY for values that are intentionally public (e.g., Stripe publishable key, PayPal client ID).
- Never log secrets, tokens, or passwords — use `[REDACTED]` if a log line needs to reference a secret field.
- Rotate secrets immediately if accidentally committed to git.
- `.env.*` files MUST be in `.gitignore` — verify on every new file creation.

#### 23.8 Output Encoding
- When generating XML feeds (`/api/feeds/*`), escape all user-provided data with an XML entity encoder.
- When generating HTML email templates, use React Email (already sanitized) — never raw string concatenation.
- PDF generation with `@react-pdf/renderer`: do NOT render raw user HTML — only use the layout primitives.

#### 23.9 HTTP Security Headers (Required in `next.config.mjs`)
All production responses MUST include:
```
Content-Security-Policy:      default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' https://connect.facebook.net https://www.paypal.com https://js.stripe.com; img-src 'self' data: blob: https:; frame-src https://js.stripe.com https://www.paypal.com;
Strict-Transport-Security:    max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload
X-Content-Type-Options:       nosniff
X-Frame-Options:              DENY
Referrer-Policy:              strict-origin-when-cross-origin
Permissions-Policy:           camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=()
X-XSS-Protection:             1; mode=block
```

#### 23.10 Dependency Security
- Run `npm audit` before every production deployment — fix `high` and `critical` vulnerabilities.
- Pin exact versions of security-critical packages (`bcryptjs`, `next-auth`, `zod`).
- Keep `next`, `react`, and `prisma` on the latest patch release within the major version.

#### 23.11 Error Handling — Never Leak Internals
- API routes MUST never return raw Prisma error messages, stack traces, or internal paths in production.
- Use a wrapper for all API errors:
  ```ts
  // ✅ Safe
  return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Product not found' }, { status: 404 });
  // ❌ NEVER
  return NextResponse.json({ error: err.message, stack: err.stack }, { status: 500 });
  ```
- Log full errors server-side (Sentry) — return only user-safe messages to the client.

#### 23.12 File Upload Security (when implemented)
- Validate MIME type server-side (never trust `Content-Type` header alone — inspect file magic bytes).
- Restrict allowed extensions: `jpg`, `jpeg`, `png`, `webp` for images.
- Set max file size limit (5MB) in the API route before storing.
- Store uploads in Supabase private buckets; generate signed URLs with short TTLs (15 minutes).
- Never store uploaded files with user-provided filenames — always generate a UUID-based path.

#### 23.13 Stripe & PayPal Webhooks
- **Always verify webhook signatures** before processing payment events:
  - Stripe: `stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(body, sig, process.env.STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET)`
  - PayPal: Verify IPN with PayPal's verification endpoint.
- Return `200` immediately for webhook endpoints to prevent retries — process asynchronously.
- Log all payment webhook events (event type + order ID) for audit purposes.

#### 23.14 WhatsApp & External API Calls
- Validate the `X-Hub-Signature-256` header on incoming WhatsApp webhooks.
- Use `WHATSAPP_VERIFY_TOKEN` for the Meta webhook verification endpoint.
- Apply outbound request timeouts (10s) to all external API calls to prevent hanging.

> **SECURITY REVIEWS**: Before launching Phase 3 (Checkout) and Phase 6 (Payments/Invoicing), perform a security review checklist against each rule above. Document findings in `.ai/context/SECURITY_REVIEW.md`.

